

Common Cyber Threats

Phishing Threat: Fake emails, texts, or websites that try to steal information.
Defense: Don't click suspicious links - Verify the sender - Use MFA.

  Malware
Threat: Harmful software that damages or steals data.

Types: Virus - Trojan - Worm - Ransomware - Spyware
Defense: Install antivirus software -  Keep software updated  - Avoid unknown downloads.


  Ransomware
Threat: Malware that locks files until money is paid.
Defense: Back up important files - Avoid suspicious links - Keep systems updated - 
  
Password Attacks
Threat: Hackers try to guess or steal passwords.
Examples: Brute Force - Dictionary Attack - Credential Stuffing
Defense: Use strong passwords - Enable MFA - Never reuse passwords.

  Social Engineering
Threat: Manipulating people into revealing information.
Examples: Impersonation - Fake tech support - Tailgating
Defense: Verify identities - Be cautious with personal information - Follow security policies.

Denial of Service (DoS)
Threat: Overloads a system so users cannot access it.
Defense: Use firewalls - Monitor traffic - Use DDoS protection services.

  Man-in-the-Middle (MITM)
Threat: An attacker intercepts communication between two parties.
Defense: Use HTTPS - Use VPNs - Avoid public Wi-Fi for sensitive activities.
  
Insider Threats
Threat: Employees or trusted users misuse access.
Defense: Limit user permissions - Monitor activity. - Conduct security training.
